HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 1247
By Powell
A RESOLUTION to honor the memory of Lawrence Richard Ahern
III of Nashville.
WHEREAS, the members of this General Assembly were greatly saddened to learn of
the passing of Lawrence "Larry" Richard Ahern III; and
WHEREAS, Larry Ahern was an exemplary gentleman and consummate professional
who worked assiduously to improve the quality of life for his fellow citizens in numerous
capacities; and
WHEREAS, born in Kingsport, Lawrence Richard Ahern III was the son of Lawrence
Richard Ahern, Jr., and Rhue Bagwell Ahern and graduated from Castle Heights Military
Academy in Lebanon in 1965; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Ahern attended Vanderbilt University, where he was elected president
of Pi Kappa Alpha fraternity and graduated with a bachelor's degree in 1969; he attended
Vanderbilt Law School and received his law degree in 1972; and
WHEREAS, a military veteran, Larry Ahern was a member of the Army ROTC and
enlisted in the United States Army, where he served with the Army reserves at the end of the
Vietnam War; and
WHEREAS, a highly successful attorney, Larry Ahern practiced bankruptcy and
commercial law in Chattanooga and Nashville for tenures at several prominent legal firms,
namely, Miller & Martin; Bass, Berry & Sims; and Burr & Forman; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Ahern retired from "big firm" practice in 2013 and limited his practice to
consulting engagements by legal and financial professionals, including expert testimony on legal
issues involving bankruptcy, commercial law, and real estate law. In 2023, he took retired
HJR1247
016663
- 1 -

partner status with Brown & Ahern, which has been designated as a Tier 1 Law Firm by U.S.
News since 2016; and
WHEREAS, sharing his legal knowledge, he served as an Adjunct Professor of Law at
Vanderbilt Law School, St. John's University Law School, and Belmont University College of
Law and was a Visiting Professor at Cumberland School of Law; and
WHEREAS, a highly respected member of the legal profession, Larry Ahern was a
Fellow of both the American College of Bankruptcy and the American College of Mortgage
Attorneys, as well as a Distinguished Fellow of the Association of Insolvency and Restructuring
Advisors (AIRA); he was certified as a Business Bankruptcy Specialist by the American Board of
Certification (ABC) in 1994; and
WHEREAS, he chaired the ABC and the Tennessee Commission on CLE and
Specialization and was a Director Emeritus of the ABC; additionally, he served on the Advisory
Board of the St. John's Bankruptcy LL.M program and was a member of the American
Bankruptcy Institute, the former Director of the AIRA, and a former Director and Chapter
President of the Turnaround Management Association; and
WHEREAS, no stranger to awards and accolades, Mr. Ahern was listed in The Best
Lawyers in America, starting in 1989, in the categories of business reorganization, creditors'
rights, and bankruptcy litigation, and he was honored by various publications based on peer
ratings such as "best of the bar" and similar honors; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Ahern was a frequent speaker and an author and co-author of
numerous books and articles on bankruptcy, commercial and real estate law, and related fields;
and
WHEREAS, an avid outdoorsman, Larry Ahern enjoyed outdoor sports with his family
and friends, including hiking, rafting, whitewater kayaking, cycling, and skiing. He taught
kayaking in Nashville and volunteered with Scouting America; and
- 2 - 016663

WHEREAS, a devoted husband, father, and grandfather, Mr. Ahern enjoyed the loving
companionship of his wife, Karen Cole Ahern, and was the proud father of Bonner Claire Ahern,
Cole Benjamin Ahern, Elizabeth (Steve) Chatham, and Kirkland (Rob) Hendrickson, and doting
grandfather of Catherine Chatham and John Chatham; and
WHEREAS, he will be sadly mourned but fondly remembered by his sister, Ann Ahern
Allen, his in-laws, George and Cindy Cole, and Martin and Eve Cole, and several beloved
nieces and nephews; and
WHEREAS, Larry Ahern leaves behind an indelible legacy of integrity and probity in
public life, compassion and loyalty in private life, and diligence and dedication in all his chosen
endeavors; and
WHEREAS, it is fitting that the members of this General Assembly should pause to
remember the bountiful life of this exceptional citizen and human being; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we honor the memory of Lawrence Richard Ahern III, reflecting fondly
upon his impeccable character and his stalwart commitment to living the examined life with
courage and conviction.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we express our sympathy and offer our condolences
to the family of Mr. Ahern.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
